      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why do Shopify stores need server-side tracking?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Since Apple's iOS 14 update in 2021, browser-based pixels miss 30–50% of conversions on Shopify stores with significant mobile traffic. Server-side tracking recovers these missing events by sending purchase data directly from Shopify's servers to ad platforms, restoring accurate ROAS reporting and improving ad optimisation signals."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between the Meta Pixel and the Meta Conversions API?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The Meta Pixel is a browser-based JavaScript snippet that fires when a customer's browser loads your page — it can be blocked by iOS, Safari ITP, and ad blockers. The Meta Conversions API (CAPI) is a server-side integration that sends the same events directly from your server to Meta, bypassing browser limitations entirely. Running both together (deduplication required) gives the most complete event coverage."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I set up server-side tracking on Shopify for free?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "CAPI Shield by Stack Architect implements Meta Conversions API and Google Enhanced Conversions server-side for Shopify stores at zero cost. It handles deduplication, event matching, and hashed customer data automatically. Setup takes under one hour and requires no coding. The full setup guide is at stackarchitect.xyz/capi-shield."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does server-side tracking affect page speed?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. Server-side tracking events fire after the purchase is completed and run on your server — they have zero impact on your storefront's page load speed, Core Web Vitals, or customer-facing performance. Browser pixels, by contrast, add JavaScript weight to every page load."
