  <h1>What is server-side tracking for Shopify?</h1>

  <p class="lead">
    <strong>Server-side tracking sends conversion events from your server directly to ad platforms</strong> — bypassing the customer's browser, iOS privacy restrictions, and ad blockers. For Shopify stores, it's the fix for the 30–50% of conversions that browser pixels miss since Apple's iOS 14 update in 2021.
  </p>

  <div class="meta-row">
    <span>UPDATED: April 2026</span>
    <span>READ TIME: 4 min</span>
    <span>CATEGORY: Tracking</span>
  </div>

  <h2>// Browser Pixels vs Server-Side Tracking</h2>
  <p>
    Traditional Shopify tracking uses browser-based pixels — JavaScript snippets that fire when a customer's browser loads your thank-you page. When a customer's iOS device blocks the pixel, or their browser has privacy restrictions that prevent it from firing, that conversion is invisible to your ad platforms. Server-side tracking bypasses the browser entirely.
  </p>

  <div class="compare">
    <div class="compare-card bad">
      <div class="compare-label">✕ BROWSER PIXEL</div>
      <div class="compare-title">Meta Pixel, GA4 tag</div>
      <ul class="compare-list">
        <li>Blocked by iOS 14+ privacy</li>
        <li>Blocked by Safari ITP</li>
        <li>Blocked by ad blockers (~25% of users)</li>
        <li>Cookie consent can prevent firing</li>
        <li>Adds JavaScript to every page</li>
        <li>30–50% event loss on mobile</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="compare-card good">
      <div class="compare-label">✓ SERVER-SIDE</div>
      <div class="compare-title">Conversions API, Enhanced Conversions</div>
      <ul class="compare-list">
        <li>Fires from server — not browser</li>
        <li>Not affected by iOS privacy</li>
        <li>Cannot be blocked by ad blockers</li>
        <li>Does not depend on cookies</li>
        <li>Zero page speed impact</li>
        <li>Near-complete event coverage</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>// How Server-Side Tracking Works on Shopify</h2>
  <p>
    When a customer completes a purchase on your Shopify store, Shopify's servers generate the order data. Server-side tracking sends a purchase event — including the order value, items purchased, and hashed customer identifiers — directly from Shopify's servers to Meta's Conversions API, Google's Enhanced Conversions endpoint, or TikTok's Events API. The customer's browser is never involved in this data transfer.
  </p>
  <p>
    Hashed customer identifiers (email address, phone number, first name, last name) are sent as SHA-256 hashes — they allow ad platforms to match the conversion to a specific user for attribution without transmitting raw personal data.
  </p>

