  <!-- FAQ ACCORDION -->
  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>// Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-question">Do I still need browser pixels if I have server-side tracking?<span class="chevron">▾</span></button>
      <div class="faq-answer">
        Yes — running both browser pixels and server-side events together (with deduplication) gives the most complete coverage. Browser pixels capture events that occur before purchase (page views, add-to-cart, checkout steps) while server-side focuses on the purchase event where accuracy matters most. Both signals together give ad platforms the strongest optimization data.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-question">What is deduplication and why does it matter?<span class="chevron">▾</span></button>
      <div class="faq-answer">
        Deduplication prevents the same conversion event from being counted twice when both browser pixel and server-side API send the same purchase event to Meta or Google. Without deduplication, a single purchase fires two Purchase events — one from the browser pixel and one from CAPI — inflating your reported conversions. Deduplication uses a shared event ID to tell the ad platform these are the same event and to count it only once. CAPI Shield handles deduplication automatically.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-question">How much does server-side tracking improve ROAS reporting?<span class="chevron">▾</span></button>
      <div class="faq-answer">
        Most Shopify stores see 20–40% more reported conversions in Meta and Google after implementing server-side tracking, depending on their audience's device mix and privacy settings. Stores with primarily iOS mobile audiences tend to see the largest improvement. This does not mean ad spend becomes more efficient automatically — it means your existing ad spend was already generating those conversions, but they were invisible to your reporting. Better data leads to better optimisation over time.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-question">Is server-side tracking GDPR and privacy compliant?<span class="chevron">▾</span></button>
      <div class="faq-answer">
        Server-side tracking using hashed customer identifiers is generally considered more privacy-preserving than browser pixels because raw personal data is never transmitted. However, GDPR compliance still requires a lawful basis for processing and appropriate disclosures in your privacy policy. Server-side tracking does not eliminate GDPR obligations — it changes the technical implementation, not the legal requirements. Consult a privacy lawyer for advice specific to your store.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

